title: For Sale:  .58 Caliber Zouave Musket
postcontent: Nice little Zouave for sale.  I cleaned the barrel up and it shoot just fine with .575 minie balls.  It has a one piece stock.  The lock is good and holds its "half cock" (that means the weapon is safe & will not go off unless in full cock & you pull the trigger).  I totally cleaned up the barrel with boiling hot water & soap.  I've seasoned the barrel with "wonderlube" so now you can shoot several shots out of it and it will not foul up like a weapon treated with petrolium based products.  I've got a "worm" for the ram rod.  With the weapon you'll get some absolutely wonderful .575 caliber miniballs and a .58 bullet mold.  The sights were changed by the previous owner (Zouave leaf sights are dreadful for shooting).  But for the price of $200 this is about the most inexpensive Civil War you can get that's in good condition.  Why am I getting rid of it?  I got a .69 1842 reproduciton rifled musket.  It's better for early war impressions.  Anyway, I would perfer to sell the weapon to a Michigan resident.  It goes for $200 to Michigan residents in the LP.  If it has to be shipped to the UP or out of state the shipping charge is $50.

It can put 5-shot groups in 2 MOA at 100 yds all day (with several sub-MOA groups mixed in)--and I haven't sandbagged it or put it in a vise or anything, that's just shooting from the grip pod (and I'm a crappy shot!). I also have a 4-reticle reflex sight with an optionally attached laser and a pressure pad. (reflex is on it now, but i can include the scope if you want)I have a grip-pod on this gun, as seen in the attached photos.  5 magazines--2x Magpul Gen3 window mags(awesome), 1x tapco AR15 Mag, and 2x steel mags. All work perfect.I currently have 922 rounds of brass cased 5.56 ammo (including 100 rounds of hollow point) to include with the deal. I can also include only 422 or 322 rounds if you would like, or zero. (All of this ammo is included in the list price) This gun has been meticulously taken care of and cleaned after every trip to the range. If you are a serious buyer, I would be happy to show you how to take it all the way down with the piston system--it's not difficult. I firmly believe that this is one of the nicest AR-15s I have ever shot, and it continually impresses me. I can honestly say that I have never had a misfire with it. I am just at a point in my life where this gun doesn't make a ton of sense for me to own. It's a great firearm and I would love to see it go to somebody who will use it and enjoy it.As always, cash talks, but I would also be interested in a trade for other firearms, or really anything of interest. title: For Sale:  Surplus Wooden Ammunition Crates
postcontent:
Hey all, I am asking $20ea individually. If you want to buy a number of them then we can talk 10-15 per crate. Worst I can say is no!I have a handful of surplus Polish Military wooden ammunition crates as well as a pair of Yugoslavian crates that I'm selling to free up some space. I'd like to keep them for long term use down the road but I already have another 20 stacked around. The polish crates are GREAT because no matter what caliber, they all share the shame dimensions and thus are PERFECT for storing a large quanity of mixed of calibers effeciently. In commercial cardboard box containers, the polish crates hold 1920 rounds of 5.56/.223 (in either 50rd or 20rd boxes), 1240 rounds of 7.62x39 (in the usual eastern block 20rd paper packed cardboard boxes), 900 rounds of 7.62x54R, or 2500 rounds of 9mm (in compact boxes, the type were the 9mm casings all touch each other in the plastic tray). It seems they don't really leave much, if any, empty space when fully packed. the 5.56/9mm packed crates I have require pull cords on one of the top layer boxes to be able to get a purchase on a box to pull out. the x39 packs a little more loosely but you still won't lose your packing organization throwing the crate around. The 7.62x54R also seems to pack damn near air tight. I am asking $20ea individually. If you want to buy a number of them then we can talk 10-15 per crate. Worst I can say is no!
